Use this toolset to investigate issues in Azure DevOps (ADO). It provides access to work items, pull requests, repositories, pipelines, and boards.

**Work item queries (WIQL):**
- Always prefer WIQL for work item searches — it is faster and more precise than free-text search
- Example: `SELECT [System.Id], [System.Title], [System.State] FROM WorkItems WHERE [System.TeamProject] = 'MyProject' AND [System.WorkItemType] = 'Bug' AND [System.State] <> 'Closed' ORDER BY [System.ChangedDate] DESC`
- Filter by area path: `[System.AreaPath] UNDER 'MyProject\\TeamA'`
- Filter by iteration: `[System.IterationPath] UNDER 'MyProject\\Sprint 42'`
- Filter by assignee: `[System.AssignedTo] = 'user@company.com'`
- Filter by tag: `[System.Tags] CONTAINS 'incident'`

**Linking incidents to code changes:**
- When investigating a production incident, search for recent PRs merged to the affected service's repo around the incident time
- Look for work items linked to the incident by searching for the incident ID or keywords in work item titles/descriptions
- Check pipeline run history to identify failed deployments that may have caused the incident

**Pull requests:**
- Search PRs by repository, branch, status (active/completed/abandoned), and date range
- Review PR descriptions and linked work items to understand what changed
- Check PR comments for reviewer concerns that may indicate known issues

**Pipelines:**
- Query recent pipeline runs to identify failed builds or deployments
- Check pipeline logs for error messages when a deployment is suspected as the root cause
- Correlate pipeline completion times with incident start times

**Best practices:**
- Start with WIQL queries scoped to the relevant project and team
- When an alert references a service name, search for it in repository names and work item area paths
- Use the `$top` parameter to limit results — default to 20-50 items to avoid token overflow
- Always include `ORDER BY [System.ChangedDate] DESC` to get the most recent items first
